Page: Changes - Fungus, Wet Rot, Dry Rot And Bacteria
Label: Revised Limit
Help: Please refer to detail help for further explanation.
HelpText: Fungus is not covered unless it is a consequence of a named peril or flood (if flood is a covered peril).  Property damage coverage is subject to a sub-limit of $15,000 per policy, applicable on an annual aggregate basis.  This is not additional insurance.  Coverage for fungus can be increased with the attachment of CP 04 31.  This form provides the ability to increase the $15,000 sub-limit for property coverage.  It also provides the ability to change the sub-limit from a per policy annual aggregate limit to an annual aggregate limit which applies separately to specified structures.  The limit can not be increased to more than applicable covered property limit.

Label: Estimated Average Value
Help: See help glossary for complete explanation.
HelpText: The value in this field is dependent on 1) whether Multiple Location Average Rates are Used or Not Used and 2) if the policy is new or renewal. When Multiple Location Average Rates are Not Used and it's a new business policy, the rating will return 75% of the Personal Property Limit as the limit to determine the provisional premium (Rule 36.G.2.b.(2)) and this field should be zero. When Multiple Location Average Rates are Used, it's a new business policy and the average limit based on the prior policies reported values is not available, this field should be populated with an estimated average limit based on the prior policies reported values. On renewal, if  Multiple Location Average Rates are Not Used and the average limit based on the prior policies reported values is not available,  this field will be populated with an estimated average limit based on the prior policies reported values (Rule 36.G.2.b.(3)). On renewal, if Multiple Location Average Rates are Used the field will be populated with an estimated average limit based on the prior policies reported values.

Label: Average Value
Help: See help glossary for complete explanation.
HelpText: Field is only valid when Multiple Location Average Rates are Used with one exception as per rule 36.G.2.b.(3).  User should enter the average value of personal property as of the policy effective date for new business only. If this value is not available then this field should be 0, and an estimated average value of personal property should be entered in the Estimated Average field above.  On renewal, if the Multiple Location Average Rates are Not Used enter the personal property average values for all of  the previous years. If this value is not available then this field should be 0, and the average limit, based on the prior policies reported values, will be held in the Estimated Average field above.

Label: Specific Insurance
Help: Enter the amount of Specific Insurance that covers the same property.

Label: Estimated Average Value - Including Value of Alcoholic Beverage Taxes
Help: See help glossary for complete explanation.
HelpText: The value in this field is dependent on 1) whether Multiple Location Average Rates are Used or Not Used, 2) whether the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form applies, 3) if the policy is new or renewal, and 4) whether theft is a covered cause of loss or not. When the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form does not apply then the field should be 0. When the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form applies, Multiple Location Average Rates are Not Used, it's a new business policy and Theft is excluded, rating returns 75% of the Personal Property Limit minus the Alcoholic Beverage Tax. If Theft is not excluded, the rating returns 75% of the Personal Property Limit. When the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form applies, Multiple Location Average Rates are Used, it's a new business policy and Theft is excluded, this field should represent the value of the personal property minus the Alcoholic Beverages Taxes. If Theft is not excluded, this field should represent the value of the personal property. On renewal, if the Multiple Location Average Rates is Used, the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form applies and Theft is excluded, this field will be populated with an average limit based on the prior policies reported values minus Alcoholic Beverage Taxes. If Theft is not excluded, this field will be populated with an average limit based on the prior policies reported values. On renewal, if the Multiple Location Average Rates is Not Used, the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form applies, average limit based on the prior policies reported values minus Alcoholic Beverage Taxes is not available and Theft is excluded, this field will be populated with an estimated average limit based on the prior policies reported values minus Alcoholic Beverage Taxes. If average limit based on the prior policies reported values is not available and Theft is not excluded, this field will be populated with an estimated average limit based on the prior policies reported values.

Label: Average Value - Including Value of Alcoholic Beverage Taxes
Help: See help glossary for complete explanation.
HelpText: When the Alcoholic Beverages Tax Exclusion form does not apply to the personal property, then the field should be 0. The field is only valid when Multiple Location Average Rates are Used with one exception as per rule 36.G.2.b.(3). If Theft is excluded, the user should enter the average value of personal property minus the value of Alcoholic Beverage Taxes, as of the policy effective date for new business only. If Theft is not excluded, the user should enter the average value of personal property as of the policy effective date for new business only. On renewal, if  the Multiple Location Average Rates are Not Used and Theft is excluded, enter the personal property average values for all of  the previous years minus the value of Alcoholic Beverage Taxes. If Theft is not excluded,  enter the personal property average values for all of  the previous years. If personal property average values for all of  the previous years is not available then this field should be 0 and the average limit, based on the prior policies reported values, will be held in the Estimated Average Value - Including Value of Alcoholic Beverage Taxes field above.

When the building is included in a blanket and Earthquake cause of loss is not included in the blanket, then a building limit, subject to the coinsurance provision, is required entry. When the building is included in a blanket, the 100% building value is used in the determination of the overall blanket limit, subject to the selected blanket coinsurance percentage.   If the building is not part of a blanket, enter the building limit resulting from application of the coinsurance percentage.
